A '''capillary''' is a single [[cell]]ed [[blood vessel]]. It does not have the muscular/elastic [[tissue (biological)|tissue]] of other blood vessels. It has a single [[cell wall|celled wall]] to help substances be transported through [[organism]]s.
Capillaries are small, and smaller than any other [[blood vessel]]s. They are about 5-10 [[micrometre|μms]] big, which connect [[arteriole]]s and [[venule]]s, and enable the moving of [[water]], [[oxygen]], [[carbon dioxide]], and many other [[nutrient]] and [[waste]] [[chemical]]  between [[blood]] and surrounding [[tissue (biology)|tissues]].<ref>{{cite book
